message.content:
We start by locating only those rows that affect the fixed assets balance.

Step‑by‑step:

1. From the initial “Initial” entries the fixed asset item is recorded as:
 • A row with type “Fixed Assets” on 2023‑12‑31 with amount = 8,000,000.00.
  This is the starting (initial) fixed assets balance.

2. Next, look for “Fixed Assets Purchase” transactions. In our data there are two such rows:
 • One row (id “FixedAsset20231231001”) for “Fixed Assets Purchase” with amount = 830,405.75 (asset “Central AC4”).
 • Another row (id “FixedAsset20231231001”) for “Fixed Assets Purchase” with amount = 383,011.45 (asset “Kitchen Equipment5”).
 Adding these gives an addition of:
  830,405.75 + 383,011.45 = 1,213,417.20.

3. Depreciation reductions:
 We see depreciation entries (they reduce the carrying value):
 • Depreciation on 2024‑01‑01 for amount = 45,745.80.
 • Depreciation on 2024‑02‑01 for amount = 69,766.11.
 Total depreciation = 45,745.80 + 69,766.11 = 115,511.91.

4. Now, compute the end net fixed asset value:
 Net end value = (Initial fixed assets + Additions from fixed asset purchases) − Depreciation
  = (8,000,000.00 + 1,213,417.20) − 115,511.91
  = 9,213,417.20 − 115,511.91
  ≈ 9,097,905.29

Thus, in our final answer we have:
 • fixed assets net Initial Value = 8,000,000.00 
 • fixed assets net End Value = 9,097,905.29
